{{Infobox person | name = Linda Day | image = | caption = | birth_name = Linda Gail Brickner | birth_date = August 12, 1938 | birth_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|2009|10|23|1938|8|12}} | death_place = [[Georgetown, Texas]], U.S. | other_names = Linda Day Varnum |occupation = Television director |years_active = 1976–2003 }} '''Linda Day''' (August 12, 1938 &ndash; October 23, 2009)<ref name="hollywoodreporter1">[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i7a4f853fe57e4c0b1d7ee42fd02b9acf ''Hollywood Reporter'' obituary] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028084435/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i7a4f853fe57e4c0b1d7ee42fd02b9acf |date=October 28, 2009 }}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[television director]], working primarily in [[situation comedy|situation comedies]].
Day was born as '''Linda Brickner'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/16/Linda-Day.html |title=Film Reference bio |publisher=Filmreference.com |date=1938-08-12 |accessdate=2012-06-25}}</ref> in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], the daughter of Roy Brickner, a film editor. At the age of 67, she married her childhood sweetheart, L. Steve Varnum, in Texas.<ref name="marr05">{{cite web|title=Marriage License Application Indexes|url=http://dshs.texas.gov/vs/marriagedivorce/marridx/marr05.ppt|website=dshs.texas.gov|publisher=Texas Department of State Health Services|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref><ref name="Hollywood">{{cite web|title=Linda Day|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/linda-day-57746835/|publisher=[[Hollywood.com]]|accessdate=29 January 2017}}</ref>
==Career== Day started as a script supervisor on the [[Television film]] ''[[Victory at Entebbe]]'', and on the [[soap opera]] parody ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]''. She became an associate director for ''[[WKRP in Cincinnati]]'' in 1978, and began directing episodes of the show in 1980. Linda Day went on to direct a number of successful [[sitcom]]s in the 1980s<ref name="Hollywood" /> and '90s, including the pilot of ''[[Married With Children]]'' and 32 more episodes of the show.<ref name="Hollywood" /> Day also directed four episodes of the soap opera ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' during what would become the show's "[[Dallas (1978 TV series) (season 9)|dream season]]" in 1985–86, when the events of the entire season were explained away as being a character's dream.<ref name="LATimes">{{cite news|author1=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=PASSINGS: Joel Murray, Linda Day Varnum|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-passings31-2009oct31-story.html|accessdate=29 January 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=31 October 2009}}</ref>
In addition to a [[Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Directing_for_a_Comedy_Series#1980s|Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]] nomination,<ref name="Emmys">{{cite web|author1=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Director Linda Day Passes|url=http://www.emmys.com/news/news/director-linda-day-passes|website=Emmys|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]]|accessdate=29 January 2017|date=20 November 2009|quote=In 1981, she earned an Emmy nomination for an episode of ''Archie Bunker’s Place''.}}</ref> she received a [[Humanitas Prize]] and was honored by the [[Directors Guild of America]] for paving the way for women in television; she directed more than 350 episodes<ref name="Variety">{{cite news|author1=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Director Linda Day dies at 71|url=https://variety.com/2009/scene/people-news/director-linda-day-dies-at-71-1118010434/|accessdate=29 January 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=26 October 2009|quote=Pioneer helmed more than 350 episodes of TV}}</ref> and 50 series.<ref name="hollywoodreporter1"/>
==Death== Linda Day died, aged 71, from cancer in [[Georgetown, Texas]]. She was survived by her husband, L. Steve Varnum; her daughter, Heidi Gutman, and her sister, Nancy Riley.
